From: JP Hein <jp@jphein.com>
Date: Fri, 21 Mar 2026 12:00:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 3/3] media: uvcvideo: add control transfer throttle quirk for
 Razer Kiyo Pro

The Razer Kiyo Pro (1532:0e05) firmware crashes when it receives rapid
consecutive UVC control transfers (SET_CUR). After approximately 25
rapid control changes, the device stops responding to USB control
transfers entirely. This triggers an xHCI stop-endpoint command timeout,
which causes the host controller to be declared dead, disconnecting
every USB device on the bus — including keyboards and mice.

The crash is reproducible with rapid v4l2-ctl SET_CUR operations on
controls like focus, white balance, exposure, and pan/tilt/zoom at
intervals under ~50ms.

The failure sequence is:

  1. Rapid SET_CUR control transfers overwhelm the camera firmware
  2. Device responds with STALL (EPIPE/-32)
  3. uvc_query_ctrl() sends a second transfer (GET_CUR for error code),
     further stressing the dying device
  4. Device firmware locks up, stops responding to all USB transfers
  5. usb_start_wait_urb() times out after 5000ms
  6. xHCI issues stop-endpoint command, which also times out
  7. "xHCI host controller not responding, assume dead"
  8. All USB devices on the controller are disconnected

Introduce UVC_QUIRK_CTRL_THROTTLE (0x00080000) to address both the
rate issue and the error amplification:

  - Enforce a minimum 50ms interval between SET_CUR control transfers,
    preventing the rapid-fire pattern that overwhelms the firmware.
    50ms allows up to 20 control changes per second, which is sufficient
    for interactive slider adjustments while keeping the device stable.

  - Skip the UVC_VC_REQUEST_ERROR_CODE_CONTROL query after EPIPE errors.
    When a SET_CUR fails, the driver normally sends a second USB transfer
    to read the UVC error code. On a device that is already stalling,
    this second transfer amplifies the problem and can push the firmware
    into a full lockup. With this quirk, EPIPE is returned directly
    without the follow-up query.

Add the Razer Kiyo Pro (1532:0e05) to the device table with this quirk,
combined with UVC_QUIRK_DISABLE_AUTOSUSPEND to prevent autosuspend from
introducing additional firmware instability.

Tested on kernel 6.8.0-106-generic with Intel Cannon Lake PCH xHCI
(8086:a36d). Without the quirk, the device crashes after ~25 rounds of
rapid control changes. With USB_QUIRK_DELAY_CTRL_MSG (200ms delay, used
as a proxy test), the device survives 500+ rounds. The 50ms throttle
in this patch is a more targeted fix that avoids penalizing all USB
control messages to the device.

Cc: stable@vger.kernel.org
Link: https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/linux/+bug/2061177
Signed-off-by: JP Hein <jp@jphein.com>
---
 drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_driver.c | 11 +++++++++++
 drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_video.c  | 22 ++++++++++++++++++++++
 drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.h   |  3 +++
 3 files changed, 36 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.h b/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.h
index XXXXXXX..XXXXXXX 100644
--- a/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.h
+++ b/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvcvideo.h
@@ -83,6 +83,7 @@
 #define UVC_QUIRK_MJPEG_NO_EOF		0x00020000
 #define UVC_QUIRK_MSXU_META		0x00040000
+#define UVC_QUIRK_CTRL_THROTTLE	0x00080000

 /* Format flags */
 #define UVC_FMT_FLAG_COMPRESSED		0x00000001
@@ -610,6 +611,8 @@ struct uvc_device {
 	u32 clock_max_gap;

 	u32 quirks;
+	/* Control transfer throttling (UVC_QUIRK_CTRL_THROTTLE) */
+	unsigned long last_ctrl_set_jiffies;
 	u32 meta_format;
 };

diff --git a/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_video.c b/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_video.c
index XXXXXXX..XXXXXXX 100644
--- a/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_video.c
+++ b/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_video.c
@@ -71,6 +71,8 @@ int uvc_query_ctrl(struct uvc_device *dev, u8 query, u8 unit,
 		    u8 intfnum, u8 cs, void *data, u16 size)
 {
 	int ret;
+	unsigned long min_interval;
+	unsigned long elapsed;

+	/*
+	 * Rate-limit SET_CUR operations for devices with fragile firmware.
+	 * The Razer Kiyo Pro locks up after ~25 rapid consecutive SET_CUR
+	 * transfers, ultimately crashing the xHCI host controller.
+	 */
+	if (query == UVC_SET_CUR &&
+	    (dev->quirks & UVC_QUIRK_CTRL_THROTTLE)) {
+		min_interval = msecs_to_jiffies(50);
+		if (dev->last_ctrl_set_jiffies &&
+		    time_before(jiffies,
+				dev->last_ctrl_set_jiffies + min_interval)) {
+			elapsed = dev->last_ctrl_set_jiffies + min_interval -
+				  jiffies;
+			msleep(jiffies_to_msecs(elapsed));
+		}
+	}
+
 	ret = __uvc_query_ctrl(dev, query, unit, intfnum, cs, data, size,
 				UVC_CTRL_CONTROL_TIMEOUT);
+
+	if (query == UVC_SET_CUR)
+		dev->last_ctrl_set_jiffies = jiffies;
+
 	if (likely(ret == size))
 		return 0;

@@ -104,6 +126,16 @@ int uvc_query_ctrl(struct uvc_device *dev, u8 query, u8 unit,
 		return ret < 0 ? ret : -EPIPE;
 	}

+	/*
+	 * Skip the error code query for devices that crash under load.
+	 * The standard error-code query (GET_CUR on
+	 * UVC_VC_REQUEST_ERROR_CODE_CONTROL) sends a second USB transfer to
+	 * a device that is already stalling, which can amplify the failure
+	 * into a full firmware lockup and xHCI controller death.
+	 */
+	if (dev->quirks & UVC_QUIRK_CTRL_THROTTLE)
+		return -EPIPE;
+
 	/* Reuse data[0] to request the error code. */
 	ret = __uvc_query_ctrl(dev, UVC_GET_CUR, 0, intfnum,
 			       UVC_VC_REQUEST_ERROR_CODE_CONTROL, data, 1,

diff --git a/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_driver.c b/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_driver.c
index XXXXXXX..XXXXXXX 100644
--- a/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_driver.c
+++ b/drivers/media/usb/uvc/uvc_driver.c
@@ -3125,6 +3125,17 @@ static const struct usb_device_id uvc_ids[] = {
 	  .bInterfaceProtocol	= 0,
 	  .driver_info		= (kernel_ulong_t)&uvc_quirk_probe_minmax },

+	/* Razer Kiyo Pro — throttle control transfers to prevent firmware
+	 * lockup that cascades into xHCI host controller death. */
+	{ .match_flags		= USB_DEVICE_ID_MATCH_DEVICE
+				| USB_DEVICE_ID_MATCH_INT_INFO,
+	  .idVendor		= 0x1532,
+	  .idProduct		= 0x0e05,
+	  .bInterfaceClass	= USB_CLASS_VIDEO,
+	  .bInterfaceSubClass	= 1,
+	  .bInterfaceProtocol	= 0,
+	  .driver_info		= UVC_INFO_QUIRK(UVC_QUIRK_CTRL_THROTTLE
+					| UVC_QUIRK_DISABLE_AUTOSUSPEND) },
+
 	/* Oculus VR Positional Tracker DK2 */
 	{ .match_flags		= USB_DEVICE_ID_MATCH_DEVICE
 				| USB_DEVICE_ID_MATCH_INT_INFO,
--
2.43.0
